bmo: Short answer: the key subcommand was removed. Recent versions of bmo no longer store or manage API keys; they read provider keys from your environment at runtime. That’s why running bmo key add now fails with “missing the API key.”

What to do instead
- Set the env var for the provider you use, e.g.:
  - OpenAI: export OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
  - Anthropic: export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=...
  - OpenRouter: export OPENROUTER_API_KEY=...
  - Groq: export GROQ_API_KEY=...
  - Mistral: export MISTRAL_API_KEY=...
  - Cohere: export COHERE_API_KEY=...
- Put that export in your shell profile (~/.zshrc, ~/.bashrc), or use a secrets manager/direnv so it’s set before running bmo.

Quick check
- echo $OPENAI_API_KEY (or the relevant var) to confirm it’s present in your shell.
- Then run bmo again with your chosen model; bmo will pick up the corresponding key automatically (e.g., gpt-* models use OPENAI_API_KEY, claude-* use ANTHROPIC_API_KEY).

If you tell me which model/provider you use, I can give the exact export lines.
